To achieve the desired result with the Fruchterman-Reingold layout in Sigma.js, you can replace the initialization and invocation of the Force Atlas 2 layout with the Fruchterman-Reingold layout as follows:

```javascript
// Replace the Force Atlas 2 layout with the Fruchterman-Reingold layout
sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.configure(sigmaInstance, { easing: 'quadraticOut' });
sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.start(sigmaInstance);

// After spawning a new node or removing a node, re-run the layout
sigmaInstance.refresh();
sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.start(sigmaInstance);
```

This code sets up the Fruchterman-Reingold layout with the specified easing option. Then, after adding or removing nodes, you need to call `sigmaInstance.refresh()` to update the Sigma instance and `sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.start(sigmaInstance)` to start the layout computation again.

Make sure to include these code snippets at the appropriate places in your Sigma.js implementation to achieve the desired behavior.

I apologize for the inconvenience. It seems that the URL provided for the Sigma.js Fruchterman-Reingold layout plugin is incorrect or outdated.

Instead, I recommend using an alternative layout plugin called `sigma.plugins.layout` with the `fruchterman` layout algorithm.

1. Download the `sigma.plugins.layout.fruchterman.js` file from this GitHub repository: [sigma.plugins.layout.fruchterman.js](https://github.com/jacomyal/sigma.js/blob/master/plugins/sigma.plugins.layout.fruchterman.js).

2. Save the downloaded file in your project directory and include it in your HTML file:

```html
<script src="path/to/sigma.plugins.layout.fruchterman.js"></script>
```

3. After including the layout plugin, you can modify the code as follows:

```javascript
// Replace the initialization and invocation of the layout
sigma.plugins.layout.fruchterman.configure(sigmaInstance, { easing: 'quadraticOut' });
sigma.plugins.layout.fruchterman.start(sigmaInstance);

// After adding or removing nodes, re-run the layout
sigmaInstance.refresh();
sigma.plugins.layout.fruchterman.start(sigmaInstance);
```

With this approach, you should be able to use the Fruchterman layout in Sigma.js without encountering any "sigma.layouts is undefined" error.

I apologize for the confusion. It seems that the animate plugin is not available in the latest version of Sigma.js (v2).

In that case, you can achieve the desired functionality with a simple workaround. Instead of using the animate plugin, you can directly update the position of the nodes in a loop using the Fruchterman-Reingold layout algorithm. Here's an example:

```javascript
// Configuration for the Fruchterman-Reingold layout
const frLayoutConfig = {
  easing: 'quadraticOut',
  iterations: 300, // Number of iterations for the layout algorithm
};

// Start the Fruchterman-Reingold layout
sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.configure(sigmaInstance, frLayoutConfig);
sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.start(sigmaInstance);

// Function to update the layout positions manually
const updateLayout = () => {
  // Run the layout algorithm for a single iteration
  sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.step(sigmaInstance);

  // Refresh the Sigma instance to apply the position updates
  sigmaInstance.refresh();

  // Check if the layout is still running
  if (!sigma.layouts.fruchtermanReingold.isRunning()) {
    clearInterval(layoutInterval);
  }
};

// Call the updateLayout function every 16ms (60fps) until the layout is complete
const layoutInterval = setInterval(updateLayout, 16);
```

In this code, we configure the Fruchterman-Reingold layout with the desired options and start it. Then, we define the `updateLayout` function, which runs a single iteration of the layout algorithm and refreshes the Sigma instance. We call this function repeatedly using `setInterval` until the layout is complete, checking if the layout is still running to stop the interval.

By using this approach, you can achieve the progressive layout update without relying on the now-removed animate plugin.

I apologize for the inconvenience once again. It seems that the Fruchterman-Reingold layout is not available as a standalone plugin in Sigma.js v2.

Instead, you can try using the OpenOrd layout as an alternative. Follow these steps to use the OpenOrd layout in Sigma.js:

1. Download the OpenOrd plugin file from this GitHub repository: [sigma.layout.openord.js](https://github.com/jacomyal/sigma.js/blob/master/plugins/sigma.layout.openord.js).

2. Save the downloaded file in your project directory and include it in your HTML file:

```html
<script src="path/to/sigma.layout.openord.js"></script>
```

3. After including the layout plugin, modify your code as follows:

```javascript
// Configure and start the OpenOrd layout
sigma.layouts.start(
  sigmaInstance,
  {
    worker: true,
    barnesHutOptimize: true,
    barnesHutTheta: 0.5,
    scalingRatio: 10,
    strongGravityMode: true,
    gravity: 1,
    slowDown: 1,
  },
  () => {
    // After the layout is complete, refresh the Sigma instance
    sigmaInstance.refresh();
  }
);

// Whenever you add or remove nodes, call the layout again
sigma.layouts.kill(sigmaInstance);
sigma.layouts.start(...);
```

In this modified code, we are using the `sigma.layouts.start()` function to configure and start the OpenOrd layout. The second argument to this function is an object containing the layout configuration options. Once the layout is complete, the callback function is executed, where you can refresh the Sigma instance to update the positions.

Whenever you add or remove nodes, you will need to stop the previous layout with `sigma.layouts.kill()` and start a new one with `sigma.layouts.start()`.

Please note that the OpenOrd layout may have different configuration options and behaviors compared to the Fruchterman-Reingold layout. You may need to adjust the configuration options based on your specific requirements.

I hope this helps, and I apologize for the previous incorrect information regarding the Fruchterman-Reingold layout.

I apologize for the inconvenience. It seems that the OpenOrd plugin for Sigma.js is not readily available.

In that case, as an alternative, you can consider using the ForceAtlas2 layout, which is included as a default layout plugin in Sigma.js v2.

To use the ForceAtlas2 layout, you can modify your code as follows:

```javascript
// Configure and start the ForceAtlas2 layout
sigma.layouts.configForceAtlas2(sigmaInstance, {
  linLogMode: false,
  outboundAttractionDistribution: false,
  adjustSizes: false,
  iterationsPerRender: 1,
  worker: true,
});
sigma.layouts.startForceAtlas2(sigmaInstance);

// After adding or removing nodes, restart the layout
sigmaInstance.graph.addNode(nodeData);  // Adding a node example
sigmaInstance.refresh();
sigma.layouts.startForceAtlas2(sigmaInstance);
```

In this code, we configure the ForceAtlas2 layout using the `sigma.layouts.configForceAtlas2()` function. Adjust the configuration options as per your requirements.

To start the layout, use the `sigma.layouts.startForceAtlas2()` function.

After adding or removing nodes, call `sigmaInstance.refresh()` to update the Sigma instance and then start the layout again with `sigma.layouts.startForceAtlas2()`.

Please note that you may need to tweak the layout configuration options and iterations based on your specific needs to achieve the desired graph layout.

Once again, I apologize for the inconvenience caused by the unavailable OpenOrd plugin, and I hope the ForceAtlas2 layout solution meets your requirements.

In Sigma.js, you can specify the minimum size of the nodes using the `minNodeSize` option in the renderer configuration. This option sets the minimum size in pixels for the nodes, ensuring that they don't shrink below a certain threshold.

Here's an example of how you can use the `minNodeSize` option in Sigma.js:

```javascript
const s = new sigma({
  renderer: {
    container: document.getElementById('sigma-container'),
    type: 'canvas',
    // Set the minimum size for the nodes
    minNodeSize: 5,
  },
  // ...other configuration options
});
```

In this example, the `minNodeSize` option is set to `5`, which means that the nodes will not shrink below 5 pixels in size.

Make sure to include this `minNodeSize` option in the renderer configuration when creating your Sigma.js instance.

By setting the `minNodeSize`, you can control the minimum size of the nodes in your Sigma.js visualization. Adjust the value as per your requirements to define the smallest size that nodes can have.
